<DOC><DOCNO> AP891114-0129 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1646EST</FILEID><FIRST>b w PM-Navy-Accidents 1stLd-Writethru a0662-a0667 11-14 0269</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Navy-Accidents, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662-a0667,280</SECOND><HEAD>Navy Shutting Down Operations After Accidents</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: RFETRANSMITS a3537 to put in correct number sequence</HEAD><BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Navy, out of concern over a string ofaccidents in recent weeks, has ordered that all normal operationscease for 48 hours while safety procedures are reviewed, theservice announced today.   ``Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III and the Chief of NavalOperations Carlisle A. H. Trost have ordered a Navy-wide 48-hoursafety stand-down to be conducted within the next 72 hours,'' theNavy said in a statement.   The order requires every ship, squadron and shore trainingfacility to interrupt normal operations and review basic safety andoperating procedures, said Navy spokesman Lt. Bruce Cole.   ``It means that they will interrupt normal training, normalflight operations, normal field operations ... to go over basicsafety procedures and make sure that everybody has the basics,''the spokesman added.   ``The purpose of the stand-down is to reemphasize continuingsafety awareness among all Navy personnel,'' Cole said.   The move comes just after the latest problem for the Navy, inwhich a fire broke out aboard the amphibious assault ship USSInchon while it underwent shipyard maintenance in Norfolk, Va., Atleast 24 people were reported injured in the incident.   In recent weeks, the service has been plagued by a number ofdeadly accidents involving a training jet crashing into an aircraftcarrier off Florida, sailors who have been washed overboard on twodifferent aircraft carriers and the accidental bombing of a ship bya Navy pilot in the Indian Ocean.</TEXT></DOC>